methodology: Rankings based on ACRUE v3 weighted_total scores averaged across 3 images per style. Technical feasibility assessment considers style accuracy, completeness, and consistency of transformation.

rankings.reasoning: Pop Art consistently achieved the highest scores across all images (91.0%, 93.1%, 91.8%). The style transformation was technically excellent with clear halftone dots, bold outlines, and limited color palettes applied uniformly. All images passed every assertion in Accuracy, Completeness, Relevance, Usefulness, and Exceptional dimensions. The style works exceptionally well for both people and food subjects.

Storybook achieved strong scores across all images (89.9%, 85.2%, 84.9%). The watercolor textures and soft color palettes were consistently applied. All assertions passed in core dimensions. Slightly lower exceptional scores compared to Pop Art, but still high-quality professional results suitable for children's content and printing.

Anime performed poorly across all images (40.8%, 10.3%, 44.8%). The style assertions are designed for human subjects (large expressive eyes, facial proportions, protagonist quality) which don't apply to the wildlife/food images in this test set. The Anime preset failed to achieve meaningful style transfer for non-human subjects, resulting in failed accuracy and exceptional dimensions.

analysis.key_insight: Pop Art's graphic simplification and bold color blocking works universally across subject types (wildlife, food), while Anime's character-focused assertions don't translate well to non-human subjects.
analysis.recommendation: For diverse image types, Pop Art provides the most reliable style transformation.
